[[File:Αυστριακό Αρχαιολογικό Ινστιτούτο.jpg|thumb|250px|The building where the Austrian Archaeological Institute is housed in Athens.]] The '''Austrian Archaeological Institute at Athens''' ({{lang-de|Österreichisches Archäologisches Institut (ÖAI) Athen}}; {{lang-el|Αυστριακό Αρχαιολογικό Ινστιτούτο Αθηνών}}) is one of the 17 [[List of Foreign Archaeological Institutes in Greece|foreign archaeological institutes]] operating in [[Athens]], [[Greece]]. It is a branch of the Austrian Archaeological Institute based in Vienna.
Founded in 1898 by [[Otto Benndorf]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kandler|first1=Manfred|title=100 JAHRE ÖSTERREICHISCHES ARCHÄOLOGISCHES INSTITUT. 1898 - 1998|url=http://homepage.univie.ac.at/elisabeth.trinkl/forum/forum0399/10oai.htm|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> it is the fifth oldest such institution in Greece. Its main role is to provide a basis for Austrian scholars active in Greece, and to facilitate Austrian-run archaeological projects in the country.
==Excavations== [[File:Aigeira2.JPG|thumb|right|The theatre of Aigeira, excavated by the ÖAI in the 1970s.]] During its long existence, the ÖAI Athen has been involved in [[excavations]] at [[Lousoi]], [[Aigeira]] and Gremoulias (all in the modern province [[Achaea|Achaia]]), at the site of [[Elis]] and in Kolonna ([[Aegina]]).
==References== {{reflist}}
==Bibliography== *E. Korka, M. Xanthopoulou, E. Konstantinidi-Syvridi (editors), ''Foreign Archaeological Schools in Greece, 160 Years'' (Athens: Hellenic Ministry of Culture), 2006, p.&nbsp;38-47.
==External links== * [http://www.oeai.at/index.php/institutsgeschichte-89.html ÖAI Athens website]
