{{Infobox military installation | name = Saint Mary's Redoubt | native_name = Ridott ta' Santa Marija | location = [[Comino]], [[Malta]] | image = | caption = | type = [[Redoubt]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|1|6|N|14|20|21.6|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} | ownership = | controlledby = | open_to_public = | built = 1716 or 1761 | used = | builder = [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] | materials = [[Limestone]] | height = | fate = Demolished | battles = | events = }}
'''Saint Mary's Redoubt''' ({{lang-mt|Ridott ta' Santa Marija}}), also known as '''Migart Redoubt''' ({{lang-mt|Ridott ta' Migart}}), was a [[redoubt]] on the island of [[Comino]] in [[Malta]]. It was built by the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] in 1716 or 1761 (sources vary) as one of a series of coastal fortifications around the Maltese Islands.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farrugia Randon|first1=Stanley|title=Heritage Saved – Din l-Art Ħelwa – 1965–2015|date=2015|publisher=Miller Distributors Ltd.|location=[[Luqa]]|isbn=9789995752132|pages=120–121}}</ref>
The redoubt was located on the northern coast of Comino, far away from the island's other defences of [[Saint Mary's Tower]] and [[Saint Mary's Battery]]. It was demolished and no traces of it can be seen today.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Comino|url=http://www.unitedcominoferries.com/comino.html|website=United Comino Ferries|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Gozo: The Isle of Joy on Stamps|date=November 2011|publisher=Gozo Philatelic Society|location=[[Victoria, Gozo|Victoria]]|page=20|url=https://www.stamps-gozo.org/pdf/isle.pdf}}</ref>
